            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How German church tax (Kirchensteuer) works</h2>
              <p>
                In Germany, church tax is a surcharge on your income tax that
                finances certain religious communities. It is collected by the
                tax office (Finanzamt) and forwarded to the churches.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Basic formula:</strong><br />
                \[ \text{Church tax} = \text{Income tax} \times \text{church tax
                rate} \]
                <ul class="mt-2 text-sm">
                  <li>
                    Rate = <strong>8%</strong> in <strong>Bavaria</strong> and
                    <strong>Baden-Württemberg</strong>
                  </li>
                  <li>Rate = <strong>9%</strong> in all other Bundesländer</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Who pays church tax?</h3>
              <p>
                You usually pay church tax if all of the following are true:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You are tax-resident in Germany and pay German income tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are officially registered as a member of a church or
                  religious community that collects church tax (e.g. Roman
                  Catholic, Evangelische Kirche).
                </li>
                <li>Your income is high enough to generate income tax.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you are not a member of such a community, or you have
                officially left the church (<em>Kirchenaustritt</em>), no church
                tax is charged.
              </p>

              <h3>State differences: 8% vs 9%</h3>
              <p>
                The percentage depends on your federal state
                (<em>Bundesland</em>), not on the church itself:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>8%</strong> of income tax: Bavaria (BY),
                  Baden-Württemberg (BW)
                </li>
                <li><strong>9%</strong> of income tax: all other states</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically applies the correct rate based on
                the state you select.
              </p>

              <h3>Example calculations</h3>
              <p>Assume your annual income tax is 10,000 €.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bavaria / Baden-Württemberg (8%)</strong>: church tax
                  = 10,000 € × 0.08 = <strong>800 €</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Berlin or NRW (9%)</strong>: church tax = 10,000 € ×
                  0.09 = <strong>900 €</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Married couples and mixed memberships</h3>
              <p>
                For married couples filing jointly, the rules can be more
                complex, especially if only one spouse is a church member. In
                some cases, a <em>special church tax on capital income</em> or a
                <em>half-splitting</em> of income tax is applied.
              </p>
              <p>This calculator uses a simplified approach:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Both spouses members</strong>: church tax is
                  calculated on the full joint income tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Only one spouse member</strong>: we approximate by
                  using half of the joint income tax as the basis.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For exact treatment in complex situations (e.g. different
                denominations, foreign income, capital gains), consult a tax
                advisor or your local Finanzamt.
              </p>

              <h3>Church tax caps (Kappung)</h3>
              <p>
                Some states offer a cap so that church tax does not exceed a
                certain percentage of your taxable income (often around 3–4%).
                This mainly affects very high earners.
              </p>
              <p>
                The optional “Apply cap” checkbox in the calculator uses a
                simplified cap model to give you an idea. Actual caps and
                thresholds differ by state and can change, so treat this as an
                estimate only.
              </p>

              <h2>How to stop paying church tax (Kirchenaustritt)</h2>
              <p>
                If you no longer want to pay church tax, you must formally leave
                the church. Simply not attending services or privately changing
                your beliefs is not enough; the authorities rely on your
                official registration status.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Make an appointment</strong> with the responsible
                  office (usually the <em>Standesamt</em>, local registry
                  office, or the district court).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bring your documents</strong> – typically your
                  ID/passport, sometimes a birth or marriage certificate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Declare your exit</strong> from the church
                  (<em>Kirchenaustritt</em>) and pay a small administrative fee.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Keep the confirmation</strong>. The office notifies
                  the tax authorities; church tax stops from the next possible
                  assessment period.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                You generally cannot reclaim church tax from past years just
                because you left later, unless there was a clear administrative
                error in your registration.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about church tax in Germany</h2>

              <h3>Is church tax mandatory?</h3>
              <p>
                Church tax is mandatory <strong>only</strong> if you are
                officially a member of a church that collects it. If you are not
                a member, or you have left the church, you do not pay church
                tax.
              </p>

              <h3>Do foreigners have to pay church tax?</h3>
              <p>
                Foreigners are treated the same as German citizens: if they are
                tax-resident in Germany and registered as members of a church
                that collects church tax, they pay it. If they are not
                registered as members, they do not.
              </p>

              <h3>Is church tax deductible?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Church tax paid is usually deductible as a
                <em>Sonderausgabe</em> (special expense) in your German income
                tax return, which slightly reduces your overall tax burden.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I change state or move abroad?</h3>
              <p>
                If you move to another German state, the applicable rate (8% or
                9%) changes according to your new residence. If you move abroad
                and are no longer tax-resident in Germany, church tax is
                generally no longer due.
              </p>

              <h3>Disclaimer</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator is for educational and planning purposes only.
                It simplifies several aspects of German tax law and cannot
                replace professional tax advice. For binding information about
                your situation, contact a qualified tax advisor
                (<em>Steuerberater</em>) or your local Finanzamt.
              </p>
